amily:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">In its most recent report the HMIC noted there were “strong arrangements at a senior level around securing good quality incident and crime data, supported by helpful plans, policies and strategies.” And an internal audit carried out earlier this year against national crime recording standards found 95% of our incidents, and 98% of crimes were being correctly recorded. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Durham Constabulary sets a high standard when recording crimes and incidents in a consistent and accurate manner and staff are made fully aware of their responsibilities. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">I remain open to any scope for improvement but I am confident our recording methods are robust and accurately reflect what is happening in our communities.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2/ </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">What, if any targets do you set </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">for your </span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">&#xa0;</span><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">police force? What impact do you think this has on police recording crime practices?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">I do have some concerns about ‘hard measures’ which I take to mean for example, to reduce crime by 10%. My concerns are heightened about such an approach when the National Statistics Office questioned the accuracy of police crime figures, when public confidence in police figures is low and when NHS are criticised for focussing on figures rather than care and corrupting figures to meet targets around waiting times for instance. It is for this reason that I wish to shift dependence towards direct feedback from the public regarding levels of satisfaction with and confidence in local policing. Throughout my policing service, I have always felt these to be much more meaningful indicators rather than crime statistics A set of performance questions have been developed to hold the Force to account and clear success criteria is defined in our priority areas. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="color:#1f497d; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p></div></body></html>